Hi, I’m back to share an update. So, everything went downhill the day after I last posted on April 22. Actually, it started mid April, a few days before I went to Arizona for the weekend- I didn’t know it at the time that it was the beginning of the hardship ahead of us. My Mom and Abuelita both fell ill. May felt like the longest month that at the end of the month we were all so exhausted.
.
Then in June, my Abuelita went to Heaven. It was very unexpected. We honestly thought she would be here for another 10 years, so it’s been really hard on my Mom. But she’s strong in the Lord and will make it through.
😌
But still, it’s sad seeing her grieving.
.
I can’t imagine losing MY mom. My heart goes out to those of you who have lost your mothers, fathers & loved ones, I’m sorry.
.
I miss you all & hope you are well. And I’ll be back on posting more updates soon!
.
PS These video clips are from my personal vlogging which will be posted on YouTube later this year. Btw, for those of you who also watch @SignedWithHeart on Youtube, I’ve started posting on YouTube again, just so you know.

Swipe left - 3 videos & 2 screenshots — Hi! :) Hope everyone’s doing well. I’m back to share an update- so it’s been 6 months since I’ve posted on Instagram everyday. 😳 I never imagined I would take a break this long. — In February I decided to take a real break from Instagram and logged out for the month of March and it was heavenly. I felt so much less stressed and I was able to focus on the new course throughout March. By the end of March, I was halfway finished with the course.
.
Then I got off track in April working nonstop on a project that was due at the end of March. I tried working on the course again after I finished the project but I couldn’t really focus. I felt tired and also I was kind of stressed out that I was behind on my schedule.
.
Thankfully, I had planned to visit my friend Estefania (@jfanii) in Arizona the weekend of 17th a few weeks earlier. I needed a break, I needed to get out of the routine. The weekend was just what I needed- lots of laughs and good conversations, relaxing but still adventurous.
.
On Saturday, Estefania had to work a couple of hours in the morning. I asked her if I could film a quick video to show what she does for work. She works as a Deaf mentor. She works with hearing parents with deaf children, teaching them sign and about raising a Deaf child and helping them build a relationship with their deaf child.
.
Learning more about her work and what others are doing to contribute to a better future for the Deaf, I’m even more inspired to keep pushing through and finishing the course. 😌 Thank you guys again for learning sign. 💛
.
Then on Sunday, I asked Estefania if we could do a quick video introducing her. I bursted out laughing when she said, “and smart” because I didn’t expect that! I kind of had to beg her to be in my video. 😆 Her sign name is the same hand movement as Mexico but with the letter F. 😄
.
Anyways, hope you enjoy the videos! ☺️
.
I will be back at the end of May with an update. Stay safe and healthy! And enjoy the warm days! ☺️
.
P.S. If you’re interested in the new beginner sign language course, you can sign up to be notified when the new course is ready. The link is on profile @signedwithheart :)

node.text:
Today is National ASL Day and I wanted to share this personal post with you guys.
.
April 15, 1817 was when the first established school for the Deaf in the United States opened.
.
I’ve always known the history of American Sign Language began with Thomas Gallaudet and Alice Cogswell… that he met this little deaf girl and… and that the Deaf university in Washington, DC was named after him. That’s all I really knew.
.
Earlier this week, I researched the history of American Sign Language to learn more about the story in detail to share in the new course, and wow- I was touched and inspired.
.
The following paragraph is *my summary* of the story from *my view*. For the full story, google “Gallaudet The Legacy Begins” then click on the first link and it will take you to Gallaudet University’s website.
.
What I didn’t know was that Thomas Gallaudet was a minister when he met the young deaf girl named Alice Cogswell. He had just graduated from seminary. He had a plan but apparently, God had a different plan for him. Meeting Alice Cogswell, his heart was touched and he was led to start the first school for deaf children in America. Alice Cogswell was one of the first seven students. It was at that school where American Sign Language started. Wow.
.
I had always planned to work in the fashion industry and eventually start my own chain of stores. But God had a different plan for my life too. My heart was touched and I was led to start a new sign language account, @signedwithheart, to help teach the basics of American Sign Language.
.
After researching, I realized that in a way I’m contributing to what God had started through Thomas Gallaudet (along with Alice Cogswell’s father, Laurent Clerc, and the community), contributing to a better future for deaf children and people.
.
Today, I’m thankful for all the people that have contributed to American Sign Language to make it what it is today. And I’m forever grateful to God for leading my parents to learn sign and sending me to a school with a Deaf / Hard of Hearing program, I seriously can’t imagine my life otherwise.
.
I’m touched and inspired to keep pushing through and (cont’d in the comments)

Happy new month!! ☺️ Swipe left for the story, keep swiping left. :) — That was back in October, a couple of weeks after I stopped posting. I was feeling discouraged (see the previous post if you missed it) so I started stress eating again. So, when the employee showed me the video on her iPhone that she was learning sign language, I was touched by her thoughtfulness and efforts to learn sign to communicate with me. And then that’s when I was reminded of my vision for Signed With Heart… to teach basic sign language so that more people would learn and use sign to communicate with the Deaf, because it really does make a difference, we always appreciate it when hearing people make an effort to communicate with us even if they only know a little. 😌 The full video (12 minutes) is on my YouTube channel if you’d like to watch it. :) youtube.com/signedwithheart
.
Anyways, so if you swiped all the way to the end… you will see that I’m now working on a new beginner sign language course!! 😅 If you’re interested, the link is in my profile to sign up to be notified when the new course is ready!! 😄
.
My new planner just came in time for March! 😄 I love the color! I chose the color teal because it reminds me of paradise, beach vacations- when I finish and launch the beginner course, I plan to book a beach vacation to celebrate!! Because it’s such a huge project!!! I started working on it in 2017 and then got overwhelmed and then started again in 2018, and then now I’m starting again and this time, I made a promise to myself to stick with it until I finish it! 😅 And I’m so excited to use the new planner to help me plan each day to finish the course this time! The planner is from @terrisavellefoy - it’s a 90 day planner with a 6am to 8pm schedule every day. 😅 Anyways, just wanted to share an update!! Don’t forget to sign up if you’re interested in knowing when the new course is ready! ☺️
.
I will be back in April with an update! Have a great month! ☺️
.

node.text:
Swipe left- 5 videos — UPDATE: Hi guys! So sorry I went MIA for months. So, what happened is I was doing too many things and just crashed one day in October, feeling discouraged and tired of always trying to keep up with everything and not truly accomplishing anything so I decided to stop posting and not posting until I figured out what to do but then days went by, weeks went by… and then months went by… 😳 I never imagined I would take a break that long. I had always been afraid of taking a break even just for a few days. It was scary for me to take a break but the thought of being in the same place one year later was even scarier so I said no- I needed a break.
.
I do plan on coming back and continue posting on @SignedWithHeart, when I’m ready. 😌 I’m doing good, just taking it one day at a time. Just wanted to share an update. Hope you guys are doing good, staying safe and healthy and hopefully this whole mask thing will end sometime this year!
.
Also, I know this is late but happy new year!! 😄 It’s a brand new year so let’s make the most of it! :)
.

Notice how I fingerspelled every word for every sign I showed you? That is how you learn new signs in real life. In ASL classrooms, often teachers would just show you signs and this is probably why most people I meet that have taken ASL classes struggle with fingerspelling receptivity, because they don’t get enough practice. 🙃
.
This is why I try to do Fingerspelling Receptivity Practice everyday here on Instagram, to help you guys practicing and improving your fingerspelling receptivity so that it would make communicating with a Deaf person easier because then you’d be able to read and understand their fingerspelling because you might not remember all the signs you learned if you don’t use or practice them. 😌
.
So, if you’ve been struggling to read fingerspelling at the slowest speed (I added in the slow motion in this video for the “slowest speed” version) like if you’re not able to identify the letters on the spot even at the slowest speed, then I encourage you to sign up for the course, it will help you practice the alphabet and improve your fingerspelling receptivity and it’s only $15. :) Link in profile to sign up @signedwithheart
.
